        section#datasets
          section
            h1 Types of Datasets

          section
            img(src="../shared_images/vad_book_alldiagrams/dataset_types.png" alt="Dataset Types: tables, network/trees fields geometry")
            div
              strong.fragment + Temporal!

          section
            h2 Tables
            div.flex.small
              div.half
                ul
                  li The vast majority of datasets
                  li.fragment Attributes (columns) + items (rows)
                  li.fragment Other dataset types are usually stored as a combination of tables

              div.half.tiny.vcentered
                span.tiny
                  include ../shared_markup/table_example.html
                div.reference
                  a(href="https://www.kaggle.com/doaaalsenani/usa-cers-dataset") Sample data from Kaggle's US Cars dataset

          section.full
            h2 File formats
            div.flex.tiny
              div.half.tiny
                h3 Comma Separated File (CSV)
                pre.small
                  code
                    include ../shared_markup/USA_cars_datasets_sample.csv

              div.half.tiny
                h3 JSON
                pre.small
                  code
                    include ../shared_markup/USA_cars_datasets_sample.json

          section
            h2 Temporal
            ul
              li Tabular + time-related attribute
              li.fragment Aggregations
              li.fragment Cyclical
              li.fragment Events or intervals
              li.fragment Seasonality patterns

          //- TODO Temporal data examples

          section
            h2 Networks
            ul
              li Nodes + links
              li.fragment Attributes on both
              li.fragment Network idioms
              li.fragment Network analytics


          //- TODO Network data examples

          section
            h2 How are networks stored?
            ul
              li Two files
              li.fragment JSON file
              li.fragment Adjacency matrix
              li.fragment Generated from any data

          section
            h2 Trees
            ul
              li Hierarchical data
              li.fragment A subset of networks
              li.fragment Deserves its own class!
              li.fragment Tree idioms
              li.fragment
                a(href="https://observablehq.com/@john-guerra/treemap-from-table?collection=@john-guerra/d3-tutorials") Can be created out of tables


          //- TODO Tree data examples

          section
            h2 How are trees stored?
            ul
              li Table with path attribute
              li.fragment JSON file
              li.fragment Generated from any data

          section
            h2 Geometry
            ul
              li Location data (usually latitutde/longitude)
              li.fragment 2D or 3D
              li.fragment Inherent shape
              li.fragment Points, routes, shapes

          section
            h2 Fields
            ul
              li Continuous
              li.fragment Sampled
              li.fragment Example: brain scan

          section
            h2 Data availability
            ul
              li Static 👉 data don't change
              li.fragment Dynamic 👉 data are constantly updating (e.g., stock prices)
              li.fragment For dynamic data, you will need a data endpoint


